Scrutiny

Target IP: 192.168.138.91
Challenge Description: N/A.

Reconnaissance


Performing a TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 192.168.138.91 -p- returns the result shown in the image above. There are three TCP ports open: SSH, SMTP, and HTTP on their standard ports. The application on port 443 mentions it is closed, maybe it is worth checking with different flags supplied by nmap.


I performed a further aggressive TCP scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 192.168.138.91 -p 22,25,80,443 against the three TCP ports and obtained the result shown in the image above. From the scan above, it discovered the hostname onlyrands.com. I will need to insert this inside my /etc/hosts file.


Using the command ffuf -u http://onlyrands.com -H "Host: FUZZ.onlyrands.com" -w /usr/share/wordlists/seclists/Discovery/DNS/subdomains-top1million-110000.txt -fs 23375, I performed a VHOST enumeration. This is done to identify any other virtual hosts. This was successfuly, as the tool discovered the name teams.onlyrands.com. I will need to insert this name inside my /etc/hosts file too.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is returned for this web application on port 80. I notice there is a Login button, next to the Search feature. I checked the different features of the website, but I did not find anything useful. I performed a directory search against onlyrands.com but I did not find anything else either.


When checking the source-code of the web application, I notice the Login button redirects to teams.onlyrands.com. Time to check this page out.


The webpage above is returned for this hostname team.onlyrands.com. This page seems to disclose the application name & version TeamCity 2023.05.4. I attempted to login using default credentials such as admin:admin, admin:root, and root:root, but I had no luck. There is an existing vulnerability for this application version. This vulnerability has the CVE ID of CVE-2023-42793. However this only affects Windows hosts. Currently the target machine is running Linux.

Exploitation

Owning the TeamCity 2023.05.4 Application via Authentication Bypass (CVE-2024-27198)


I did further enumeration and found two recent vulnerabilities, as shown in the image above. The vulnerability with the CVE ID of CVE-2024-27198 is an authentication bypass vulnerability. Since I do not have any credentials so far, I can attempt to use this exploit this vulnerability. This vulnerability affects versions less than 2023.11.3, which is compatible with our target version. I searched for public exploits and found this GitHub repository. This exploit creates a new administrator account on the TeamCity application. I made a copy of the exploit on my machine.


Using the command python3 exp.py -t http://teams.onlyrands.com/login.html -u pwnedadm -p pwnedadm, I ran the exploit against the target machine. And bingo! The output mentions the new admin user has been created. The new user is pwnedadm:pwnedadm.


After logging in with the new credentials, I gained administrator access on the TeamCity application as shown in the image above. Time to enumerate further. From previous experience, I know it is possible to obtain a reverse shell connection by creating a custom script build (as shown here and here). Before doing this, I wish to enumerate any active projects.


There is one project active: Freelancers. There are multiple users assigned to this project. Maybe I can find any useful changes inside the log? I decided to check from bottom and found something with the title Oops.


When checking the change with the title Oops made by marcot, I identified the crucial information shown above. This user accidentally uploaded their SSH key and they removed it. However, the file is attached meaning I can still access it :) If this is the user's SSH key, I can attempt to gain entry to the SSH application using this key as marcot?


I copied the content of id_rsa to my machine. Since the SSH key is passphrase protected, I used the command ssh2john id_rsa > hash to obtain the passphrase password hash. Then using the command john hash --wordlist=/usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt, I managed to crack the password hash and obtain the password cheer. This user is using a very weak password.


Obtaining a foothold access on the target machine was easy due to the SSH key belonging to the user marcot. Using the command ssh marcot@onlyrands.com -i id_rsa, and the password cheer, I managed to gain access on the target machine. Now I have a foothold as the user marcot on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation

Horizontal Privilege Escalation: user marcot to matthewa via Hardcoded Password Inside Email

There are multiple users on the machine. But I do not have access to their files. When scanning this machine for the first time, I noticed SMTP is active. I ran the command mail and obtained the output shown in the image above. There are multiple emails.


With the mail terminal application open, I read the first email by entering the number 1 and received the output shown in the image above. This email contains the password IdealismEngineAshen476 belonging to the user matthewa. Can I switch to this user using the binary su?


And bingo! I ran the command su matthewa and the password IdealismEngineAshen476 and gained access, as shown in the image above. It seems like the user dach has forgot to disable the account matthewa. This user matthewa also mentioned in the email they have left something for us.

Horizontal Privilege Escalation: user matthewa to user briand via Hardcoded Password Inside File

After logging in as the user matthewa, I checked their home directory using the command ls -la and obtained the output shown above. There is one file called .~. Running cat .~ shows the content of the file. This file contains the password RefriedScabbedWasting502 belonging to the user dach. Since there is no username called dach, I have to find who this person represents.


When checking the /home/administration, I notice the user brian has a last name that begins with d. Is this the user dach? I ran the command su briand and the password RefriedScabbedWasting502 and got a hit. This new user briand belongs to the administration group.

Vertical Privilege Escalation: user briand to root via systemctl status Abuse

Since this new user has more privileges. I ran the command sudo -l and obtained the information shown in the image above. The command /usr/bin/systemctl status teamcity-server.service can be executed with root privileges. The status command can be used to obtain more information about the service. This can be abused to open a shell, which in this case a root shell.


To obtain a root shell, I entered the command sudo -u root /usr/bin/systemctl status teamcity-server.service. Then I opened a shell session by entering the command !sh as shown above. Now I have a root level access on the target machine.
